# Tiny UI Renderer — Learning React (Checklist)

## Phase 0: Tooling & Setup (Do Once)

* [ ] Use **Bun** as the dev server (static file server only)
* [ ] Use **Babel** to compile JSX → `createElement` calls
* [ ] Bundle everything into `public/main.js` using `bun build`
* [ ] Ensure all UI code runs **in the browser**, not on the server
* [ ] Server responsibility:

  * [ ] Serve `index.html`
  * [ ] Serve `main.js`
  * [ ] Do NOT render HTML on the server

### Tooling rules

* JSX is compiled at **build time**
* No JSX parsing at runtime
* No `jsdom`
* No React dependency

---

## Phase 1: JSX → Virtual DOM

### JSX compilation

* [ ] Configure Babel with `@babel/preset-react`
* [ ] Use **classic runtime**
* [ ] Point JSX factory to **your own `createElement`**
* [ ] Add `/** @jsx createElement */` pragma
* [ ] Use `.tsx` for JSX files

### TypeScript support

* [ ] Set `jsx: "react"` in `tsconfig.json`
* [ ] Set `jsxFactory: "createElement"`
* [ ] Add `src/jsx.d.ts` defining `JSX.IntrinsicElements`

---

## Phase 2: Virtual DOM Structure

* [ ] Define a `DOMElement` type:

  * [ ] `type: string` (`"div"`, `"p"`, `"text"`)
  * [ ] `props: object`
  * [ ] `children: DOMElement[]`
  * [ ] `dom: HTMLElement | Text | null`

### Rules

* [ ] VDOM contains **descriptions only**
* [ ] No real DOM nodes inside VDOM
* [ ] Text nodes are explicit (`type: "text"`)

---

## Phase 3: `createElement`

* [ ] Implement `createElement(type, props, ...children)`
* [ ] Normalize children into an array
* [ ] Convert strings/numbers into `"text"` nodes
* [ ] Do NOT handle DOM here

### Goal

* JSX becomes **plain JavaScript objects**
* JSX stops feeling magical

---

## Phase 4: Initial Mount (First Render)

* [ ] Implement `mount(vNode)`
* [ ] Create real DOM nodes using:

  * [ ] `document.createElement`
  * [ ] `document.createTextNode`
* [ ] Apply props:

  * [ ] Attributes
  * [ ] Event listeners (`onClick`, etc.)
* [ ] Recursively mount children
* [ ] Store DOM reference on `vNode.dom`

### Rule

* [ ] Mount creates DOM
* [ ] Render creates VDOM

---

## Phase 5: Render Loop

* [x] Create a `render()` function
* [x] Track the **previous VDOM tree**
* [x] On first render:

  * [x] Mount entire tree
* [x] On update:

  * [x] Create new VDOM
  * [x] Diff with old VDOM

---

## Phase 6: Re-render Everything (Before Diffing)

* [ ] On state change:

  * [ ] Re-run component function
  * [ ] Replace entire DOM tree
* [ ] Do NOT optimize yet

### Purpose

* Understand re-rendering clearly
* Confirm correctness before diffing

---

## Phase 7: Minimal Diffing

* [ ] Implement `diff(oldNode, newNode, parentDom)`
* [ ] Handle only:

  * [ ] Node created
  * [ ] Node removed
  * [ ] Type changed → replace
  * [ ] Text changed → update
  * [ ] Same type → update props + children
* [ ] Children diffed by index only
* [ ] No keys
* [ ] No reordering

### Learning goal

* Understand why React keeps previous trees

---

## Phase 8: Props & Events Update

* [ ] Add prop diffing:

  * [ ] Add new props
  * [ ] Update changed props
  * [ ] Remove missing props
* [ ] Handle events explicitly:

  * [ ] Remove old listeners
  * [ ] Add new listeners

---

## Phase 9: Hooks System (`useState`)

* [ ] Create a `hooks` array
* [ ] Create a `hookIndex`
* [ ] Reset `hookIndex` before each render

### `useState`

* [ ] Initialize state on first render
* [ ] Read state by call order
* [ ] `setState` updates value
* [ ] `setState` triggers re-render

### Learning goal

* Understand why hooks must be called in the same order

---

## Phase 10: Effects (`useEffect`)

* [ ] Collect effects during render
* [ ] Run effects after DOM updates
* [ ] Store cleanup functions
* [ ] Run cleanup before next effect
* [ ] Compare dependencies shallowly

### Learning goal

* Understand render vs commit phases

---

## Phase 11: Demo Component

Build **one** component demonstrating:

* [ ] State updates
* [ ] Event handling
* [ ] Conditional rendering
* [ ] Effects + cleanup

Examples:

* Counter
* Toggle
* Input field

---

## Phase 12: Write the Learning Summary

Document:

* [ ] What you built
* [ ] Why JSX is not runtime magic
* [ ] Why re-rendering is normal
* [ ] Why hooks rely on order
* [ ] Why effects run after DOM updates
* [ ] What React does beyond this project

---

## Stop Condition

You can stop when:

* [ ] State updates feel predictable
* [ ] Hooks rules feel obvious
* [ ] DOM updates make sense
* [ ] React no longer feels magical

---

## Final Principle

> React is a UI calculation engine that happens to target the DOM.

---
